Whitman's ink alterations to the "Live Oak" poems display a level of care and neatness of execution that indicates considerable concern to preserve their neat appearance. But no such care is evident in his pencil alterations, in which cancellations appear not as precise diagonal slashes and single horizontal strikes but as rapidly executed cross-outs and scribbled blots (e.g., 2.3 with
